.TH "PG_HARDSTORAGE" "1" "May 2026" "pg_hardstorage Manual" "pg_hardstorage Manual"

.SH NAME
.PP
pg_hardstorage-repo-audit - Comprehensive read-only repository state report


.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\fBpg_hardstorage repo audit  [flags]\fP


.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
repo audit walks every deployment + every visible manifest in the
repo and produces a comprehensive state report covering:

.RS
.IP \(bu 2
per-deployment lifecycle (active / tombstoned / held counts,
oldest / newest backup, latest backup metadata, encryption
posture, KEK refs, schema versions, PG-version spread,
timeline spread)
.IP \(bu 2
fleet-wide rollups (KEK ref → manifest count, schema-version
distribution, replica completeness)
.IP \(bu 2
audit-chain summary (event count, last-anchor age,
head-pointer presence)
.IP \(bu 2
storage usage (objects / bytes per category — same shape as
repo usage)
.IP \(bu 2
approval-request lifecycle counts
.IP \(bu 2
WORM mode + retention from HSREPO

.RE

.PP
The report is a snapshot of FACTS, not a verdict — it surfaces
the data an operator needs to answer "are all my fleets'
backups encrypted under the expected KEK?", "how many manifests
are still on the old schema?", "which deployments are missing
replica copies?" — without prescribing what's "broken". For
operational health checks (something is actively wrong), use
\fBpg_hardstorage doctor\fR; for per-backup integrity, use
\fBpg_hardstorage verify\fR\&.

.PP
Read-only by construction; safe at any cadence.

.PP
Optional opt-outs cut runtime on huge fleets:
  --no-storage     skip the per-category storage walk
  --no-chain       skip the audit-chain summary
  --no-approvals   skip the approval-request lifecycle scan


.SH OPTIONS
.PP
\fB--deployment\fP=""
	restrict the per-deployment section to one deployment (fleet rollups still cover all deployments)

.PP
\fB-h\fP, \fB--help\fP[=false]
	help for audit

.PP
\fB--no-approvals\fP[=false]
	skip the approval-request lifecycle scan

.PP
\fB--no-chain\fP[=false]
	skip the audit-chain summary (cheaper on long chains)

.PP
\fB--no-storage\fP[=false]
	skip the per-category storage usage scan (cheaper on huge repos)

.PP
\fB--repo\fP=""
	repository URL — must already exist (positional  is also accepted)


.SH OPTIONS INHERITED FROM PARENT COMMANDS
.PP
\fB--airgapped\fP[=false]
	refuse outbound endpoints (LLM providers, sinks, OTLP collectors) outside loopback / RFC1918 / explicit airgap.allowlist. Also enabled by PG_HARDSTORAGE_AIRGAPPED=1 or \fBairgapped: strict\fR in the config file.

.PP
\fB-c\fP, \fB--config\fP=""
	path to config file (default: XDG/FHS lookup)

.PP
\fB--cpu-profile\fP=""
	write a pprof CPU profile to this path for the duration of the command (\fBgo tool pprof <path>\fR to analyse). Off when empty.

.PP
\fB--mem-profile\fP=""
	write a pprof heap profile to this path at command exit. Off when empty.

.PP
\fB--no-color\fP[=false]
	disable ANSI color in text output

.PP
\fB--on-error-llm\fP[=false]
	on a structured-error failure, drop into the matching LLM helper skill (auto_on_error trigger). Also enabled by PG_HARDSTORAGE_ON_ERROR_LLM=1.

.PP
\fB--otel-endpoint\fP=""
	OpenTelemetry OTLP/HTTP endpoint (e.g. http://otel-collector:4318); empty disables tracing

.PP
\fB--otel-stdout\fP[=false]
	also export OpenTelemetry traces to stderr (useful for dev)

.PP
\fB-o\fP, \fB--output\fP=""
	output format: text|json|ndjson|yaml|template|csv|markdown|html|tap|junit|pdf (default: text on TTY, json off-TTY)

.PP
\fB--profile-port\fP=0
	if non-zero, expose net/http/pprof on 127.0.0.1: for live profiling of long-running commands (e.g. \fBgo tool pprof http://127.0.0.1:6060/debug/pprof/profile?seconds=30\fR). Off when zero.

.PP
\fB-q\fP, \fB--quiet\fP[=false]
	suppress non-essential output

.PP
\fB--template\fP=""
	Go text/template applied when --output template (or implied if --template is set without --output)


.SH SEE ALSO
.PP
\fBpg_hardstorage-repo(1)\fP
